ERR-ANALYS update.
Thirteen semiconductor detectors were used for
the angular distributions measurements. Of these,
twelve were mounted on three rotatable arms in sets of
four. The remaining counter fixed on the fourth arm was
used for measurements of scattering at extreme backward
angles. Each counter was attached to a small supporting
table which enabled three independent movements for
accurate alignment. The angular resolution of the
counter used for large-angle measurements was about
+ -5 min, while the other counters had an angular
resolution of about + -25 min.
The relative errors in the experimental
differential cross section values vary from 1% to 4%
in the deep minima, however, they reach a value of 10%.
Systematic error
The 120 cm cyclotron was used with the
160 cm diam. scattering chamber.
Alpha particle beam.
The solid angle of each counter was measured in a
special experiment using the Rutherford scattering of
alpha particles on a gold target. The intensity of the
beam was also monitored by a semiconductor detector
counting alpha particles scattered from a gold foil
placed in the beam in front of the Faraday cup.
The energy of the beam was measured by means of the
differential absorption method using Al foils as
absorbers.
A 0.6 mg/cm2 thick layer of K2O on a thin carbon
backing was used as the potassium target. This layer
was obtained by evaporation of natural potassium onto
a carbon foil and subsequent oxidation for a few
minutes in an evaporation device connected with the
scattering chamber. The target was shifted under
vacuum from the evaporation device to the centre of
the scattering chamber.
